  "eprint": {
    "title": "On One-way Functions and Sparse Languages",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Yanyi Liu",
        "email": "yl2866@cornell",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Rafael Pass",
        "email": "edurafael@cs",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "We show equivalence between the existence of one-way\r\nfunctions and the existence of a \\emph{sparse} language that is\r\nhard-on-average w.r.t. some efficiently samplable ``high-entropy''\r\ndistribution.\r\nIn more detail, the following are equivalent:\r\n  - The existence of a $S(\\cdot)$-sparse language $L$ that is\r\n    hard-on-average with respect to some samplable distribution with\r\n    Shannon entropy $h(\\cdot)$ such that $h(n)-\\log(S(n)) \\geq 4\\log n$;\r\n  - The existence of a $S(\\cdot)$-sparse language $L \\in\r\n    \\NP$, that is\r\n    hard-on-average with respect to some samplable distribution with\r\n    Shannon entropy $h(\\cdot)$ such that $h(n)-\\log(S(n)) \\geq n/3$;\r\n  - The existence of one-way functions.\r\n\r\nOur results are inspired by, and generalize, the recent elegant paper by Ilango, Ren and Santhanam (ECCC'21), which presents similar characterizations for concrete sparse languages.",
    "keywords": [
      "one-way functions",
      "average-case complexity"
    ],
    "category": "Foundations",
    "publication_info": "Preprint.",
    "last_updated": "2023-02-10",
    "license": "CC BY",
    "related_papers": []
  }
